    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Idea of Jerusalem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jacob B Ukeles letter disputes Thomas L Friedman's August 11 Op-Ed column on uniting Jerusalem</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Uniting Jerusalem,'' by Thomas L. Friedman (column, Aug. 11):</p>
        <p>Mr. Friedman says what the Jewish people have been praying for all these years ''was control of the Western Wall, the Temple Mount, the Jewish Quarter, the Mount of Olives and Mount Scopus. .  .  . But the price is letting go of the Arab-Muslim parts of the city.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Uniting Jerusalem,'' by Thomas L. Friedman (column, Aug. 11):</p>
        <p>Mr. Friedman says what the Jewish people have been praying for all these years ''was control of the Western Wall, the Temple Mount, the Jewish Quarter, the Mount of Olives and Mount Scopus. .  .  . But the price is letting go of the Arab-Muslim parts of the city.''</p>
        <p>For those of us who face Jerusalem and the Temple Mount in our daily prayers, Jerusalem is not about holy sites.</p>
        <p>Jerusalem, as a whole, is the physical embodiment of the spiritual center of the Jewish people. The Temple Mount, not the Western Wall, is the core of the center. We have prayed for two millenniums for the restoration of Jewish sovereignty in our homeland, and we continue to pray for the peaceful restoration of Jewish worship on the Temple Mount.</p>
        <p>JACOB B. UKELES  Bronx, Aug. 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
